Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Bluetongue is an arthropod-borne viral (arboviral) disease of ruminants of variable clinical severity characterised by inflammation of mucous membranes, widespread haemorrhages and oedema (Note: see epidemiological comment). Ten of the 26 internationally recognised serotypes of bluetongue virus (BTV) and several related viruses in the _Orbivirus_ genus have been recorded in northern Australia, although some of these serotypes are detected infrequently http://www.animalhealthaustralia.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/BTV3.2-13-FINAL8Jul13.pdf.

This is the 1st time that BTV-5 has been reported in Australia.

A static image of the current zoning map (updated 24 Apr 2015) is available at http://namp.animalhealthaustralia.com.au/public.php?page=namp_map&raw=1&aha_program=2&recid=101. - Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3328297,45653.]
